      <body>
         <div type="entry">
                <head>Abrohom II Gharīb</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Abrohom-II-Gharib</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/26</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">17</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="9"/>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/257</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Minor liturgical writer and <abbr>
                            <choice>
                                <sic>Patr.</sic>
                                <corr>patr.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr> (1382-1412).<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(d. 1412) [<abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr>]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Minor liturgical writer and <abbr>
                            <choice>
                                <sic>Patr.</sic>
                                <corr>patr.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr> (1382–1412). He became a monk at <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/al-Zafaran-Dayr">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/69">Dayr
                            al-Zaʿfarān</placeName>
                        </ref> before 1355, and was consecrated <abbr>bp.</abbr> of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Amid">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/8">Amid</placeName>
                        </ref> in
                        1375. He wrote an Anaphora composed from earlier Anaphoras
                        (<abbr>ms.</abbr>
                        <abbr> Syr. Orth.</abbr>
                        <abbr> Patr.</abbr> Libr.), and a <hi rend="italic">ḥusoyo</hi> for
                        Saturday of Easter week.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="bibl">
                    <head>Sources</head>
                    <listBibl>
                        <bibl>Barsoum, <title rend="italic">Scattered pearls</title>,
                            495.</bibl>
                        <bibl>Dolabani, <title rend="italic">Patriarchen</title>, 187.</bibl>
                    </listBibl>
                </div>
